<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<section xml:id="sec_control_fundamentals" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Control Fundamentals: Open-Loop vs. Closed-Loop</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Control systems are the mechanisms by which robots achieve desired behaviors. 
      Understanding the difference between open-loop and closed-loop control is 
      essential for designing effective robotic systems.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_openloop">
    <title>Open-Loop Control</title>
    <p>
      <term>Open-loop control</term> (also called <term>feedforward control</term>) 
      is a control strategy where the controller generates commands based solely on 
      the desired output, without measuring the actual output.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def_openloop">
      <statement>
        <p>
          An <term>open-loop control system</term> operates without feedback. The 
          controller generates control signals based only on a reference input and 
          a model of the system, without comparing the actual output to the desired output.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Characteristics of open-loop control:
      <ul>
        <li>Simple to implement and understand</li>
        <li>Fast, with no measurement delays</li>
        <li>Cannot compensate for disturbances</li>
        <li>Cannot correct for modeling errors</li>
        <li>Accuracy depends entirely on the accuracy of the system model</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example_openloop">
      <title>Toaster as Open-Loop System</title>
      <p>
        A traditional toaster is an open-loop system. You set the darkness level 
        (the input), and the toaster heats for a predetermined time based on that 
        setting. The toaster doesn't measure how brown the bread actually is; it 
        just runs for the programmed duration. If the bread starts out frozen or 
        if the room temperature changes, the toast may come out under- or over-cooked 
        because the system cannot adapt.
      </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example_openloop_robot">
      <title>Open-Loop Robot Motion</title>
      <p>
        Consider a robot commanded to move forward 1 meter. In open-loop control, 
        the system might:
        <ol>
          <li>Calculate that the motors should run at a specific speed for 2 seconds</li>
          <li>Send this command to the motors</li>
          <li>Wait 2 seconds</li>
          <li>Stop the motors</li>
        </ol>
        If the robot encounters unexpected friction, a slippery surface, or carries 
        a heavy load, it may not travel exactly 1 meter because there's no feedback 
        to detect and correct the error.
      </p>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_closedloop">
    <title>Closed-Loop Control</title>
    <p>
      <term>Closed-loop control</term> (also called <term>feedback control</term>) 
      is a control strategy that measures the actual output and adjusts the control 
      signal to minimize the difference between the desired and actual outputs.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def_closedloop">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>closed-loop control system</term> uses feedback from sensors to 
          continuously measure the system's output and adjust the control signal to 
          reduce the <term>error</term> (the difference between the desired output 
          and the actual output).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Characteristics of closed-loop control:
      <ul>
        <li>Can compensate for disturbances and modeling errors</li>
        <li>More accurate and robust than open-loop control</li>
        <li>Requires sensors to measure the output</li>
        <li>More complex to design and implement</li>
        <li>May suffer from stability issues if not properly tuned</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example_closedloop">
      <title>Thermostat as Closed-Loop System</title>
      <p>
        A home thermostat is a closed-loop system. It continuously measures the 
        room temperature (the output) and compares it to the desired temperature 
        (the setpoint). If the room is too cold, it turns on the heater. If it's 
        too warm, it turns off the heater or turns on the air conditioning. This 
        feedback allows the system to maintain the desired temperature despite 
        changes in outside temperature, open windows, or people entering the room.
      </p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example_closedloop_robot">
      <title>Closed-Loop Robot Motion</title>
      <p>
        Using closed-loop control, the same robot moving 1 meter would:
        <ol>
          <li>Continuously measure its position using wheel encoders or other sensors</li>
          <li>Calculate the error (desired position minus current position)</li>
          <li>Adjust motor speeds based on the error</li>
          <li>Continue until the error is nearly zero (reached the goal)</li>
        </ol>
        This approach automatically compensates for friction, slopes, or load variations, 
        ensuring the robot reaches the target accurately.
      </p>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_feedback_components">
    <title>Components of a Feedback Control System</title>
    <p>
      A typical closed-loop control system consists of several key components:
    </p>

    <dl>
      <li>
        <title>Reference Input (Setpoint)</title>
        <p>The desired value of the output (e.g., desired position, velocity, or temperature)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Controller</title>
        <p>Processes the error signal and generates the control command</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Actuator</title>
        <p>Applies the control command to the system (e.g., motor, heater)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Plant (Process)</title>
        <p>The system being controlled (e.g., robot, heating system)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Sensor</title>
        <p>Measures the actual output of the system</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Error Signal</title>
        <p>The difference between the reference input and the measured output: <m>e(t) = r(t) - y(t)</m></p>
      </li>
    </dl>

    <figure xml:id="fig_closedloop">
      <caption>Block Diagram of a Closed-Loop Control System</caption>
      <description>Block diagram showing feedback control loop</description>
      <image width="80%">
        <description>Block diagram with: Reference Input -> Comparator -> Error -> Controller -> Actuator -> Plant -> Output, with Sensor feeding back from Output to Comparator</description>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[auto, node distance=2cm, >=latex']
            \tikzset{
              input/.style={coordinate},
              output/.style={coordinate},
              block/.style={rectangle, draw, fill=blue!20, text width=5em, text centered, rounded corners, minimum height=2em},
              sum/.style={circle, draw, fill=blue!20, minimum size=6mm, node contents={}}
            }
            
            \node [input] (input) {};
            \node [sum, right of=input] (sum) {};
            \node [block, right of=sum, node distance=2.5cm] (controller) {Controller};
            \node [block, right of=controller, node distance=2.5cm] (actuator) {Actuator};
            \node [block, right of=actuator, node distance=2.5cm] (plant) {Plant};
            \node [output, right of=plant, node distance=2cm] (output) {};
            \node [block, below of=plant] (sensor) {Sensor};
            
            \draw [->] (input) -- node {$r(t)$} (sum);
            \draw [->] (sum) -- node {$e(t)$} (controller);
            \draw [->] (controller) -- node {$u(t)$} (actuator);
            \draw [->] (actuator) -- (plant);
            \draw [->] (plant) -- node [name=y] {$y(t)$} (output);
            \draw [->] (y) |- (sensor);
            \draw [->] (sensor) -| node [pos=0.95] {$-$} (sum);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_comparison">
    <title>When to Use Open-Loop vs. Closed-Loop</title>
    <p>
      Choosing between open-loop and closed-loop control depends on the application 
      requirements:
    </p>

    <p>
      <em>Use open-loop control when:</em>
      <ul>
        <li>The system is simple and well-understood</li>
        <li>Disturbances are minimal or predictable</li>
        <li>Sensors are unavailable, unreliable, or too expensive</li>
        <li>Speed is critical and feedback delays are unacceptable</li>
        <li>High accuracy is not required</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      <em>Use closed-loop control when:</em>
      <ul>
        <li>High accuracy is required</li>
        <li>The system is subject to disturbances</li>
        <li>The system model is uncertain or changes over time</li>
        <li>Reliable sensors are available</li>
        <li>The benefits of accuracy outweigh the added complexity</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      In practice, many robotic systems use a combination of both: feedforward control 
      (based on models) provides the main control effort, while feedback control makes 
      small corrections to handle uncertainties and disturbances.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec_performance">
    <title>Control Performance Metrics</title>
    <p>
      When evaluating control systems, we consider several performance metrics:
    </p>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li><em>Steady-State Error:</em> The difference between desired and actual output after transients have died out</li>
        <li><em>Rise Time:</em> How quickly the system responds to a change in setpoint</li>
        <li><em>Settling Time:</em> How long it takes to reach and stay within a specified range of the setpoint</li>
        <li><em>Overshoot:</em> How much the system exceeds the setpoint before settling</li>
        <li><em>Stability:</em> Whether the system remains bounded and converges to the setpoint</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      These metrics help us design and tune control systems to meet specific application requirements.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <conclusion>
    <p>
      Understanding the difference between open-loop and closed-loop control is 
      fundamental to robotics. While open-loop control is simpler, closed-loop control 
      with feedback is essential for achieving the accuracy and robustness required in 
      most robotic applications. In the next section, we'll explore one of the most 
      widely used feedback control strategies: PID control.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
</section>
